00:44:10.314 --> 00:44:13.250
in mathematics from Yale,
Hopper served in the Navy

00:44:13.250 --> 00:44:15.352
during World War II,
becoming one of the first

00:44:15.352 --> 00:44:17.321
programmers in
early computing.

00:44:17.321 --> 00:44:20.958
Known today as the "Queen of
Code," Grace Hopper's work

00:44:20.958 --> 00:44:23.260
helped make the coding
language more practical

00:44:23.260 --> 00:44:24.428
and accessible.

00:44:24.428 --> 00:44:27.197
She invented the first
compiler, or translator, a

00:44:27.197 --> 00:44:29.833
fundamental element of
our now digital world.

00:44:29.833 --> 00:44:32.236
"Amazing Grace" was
committed to making the

00:44:32.236 --> 00:44:34.872
language of computer
programming more universal.

00:44:34.872 --> 00:44:37.341
Today, we honor her
contributions to computer

00:44:37.341 --> 00:44:40.377
science and the sense of
possibility she inspired in

00:44:40.377 --> 00:44:41.712
generations of young people.

00:44:41.712 --> 00:44:43.714
(applause)

